[3]
Date: 11 Jun 2001 10:48:32 -0700 (PDT)
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: South China Morning Post, Associated Press Report, Sat 9 Jun 2001
[edited]
<http://news.scmp.com/ZZZHJPEDPNC.html>

Suspected Case of vCJD in Hong Kong: Alternate AP Report
--------------------------------------------------------
HONG KONG: Health authorities announced on Sat 9 Jun 2001 that they have
found the first suspected [human] case of mad cow disease in Hong Kong,
sparking fears that the deadly illness had finally spread here. Director of
Health Margaret Chan Fung Fu-chan confirmed a media report that a man
believed to have shown symptoms of the brain-wasting illness has been
hospitalized, but did not identify him. The patient has lived abroad for
many years and sought medical treatment when he returned to Hong Kong at
the beginning of this year, Dr Chan said. However, Dr Chan said the patient
had never donated blood, a possible [but unproven - Mod.] means of
spreading the disease, during his stay in Hong Kong and urged the public
not to grow prematurely fearful of contagion as the territory has banned
beef imports from Britain since 1996. "I must stress that it is still a
suspected case at this stage and the experts are still investigating," she
said.
Variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease [abbreviated as vCJD or CJD (new var.)]
has killed more than 80 Europeans since the mid-1990s, mostly in Britain.
Humans are believed to contract the illness by eating meat products from
cattle with bovine spongiform encephalopathy, or mad cow disease. It
usually manifests itself in people in the form of depression, memory loss
and dementia, with spongiform changes in the brain. In the past years, mad
cow disease and the unrelated livestock disease, foot-and-mouth disease,
have prompted many Asian countries to ban meat imports from European
countries including Britain, France and Germany, devastating the farming
industry there.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This Associated Press report is virtually identical to that preceding it,
with the single exception that the patient has changed sex from female to
male. It can be assumed now that there is in fact only one case (a male
patient) of suspected vCJD in Hong Kong. - Mod.CP]
